text: I saw the original short film which scared the crap out of me, mostly because it had no explanation whatsoever on what whats going on, the shadow just appeared and that was it. The trailer was going well for me up until 1:15, and then it just went downhill,  is very obvious that they are giving the "shadow" a backstory, the line from the trailer; " I had a friend named Diana... and something really bad happened to her" is such a cliche line from modern horror films, just as the "I have a picture with my childhood friend, where she looks creepy as hell, just to show you that she was always weird" cliche (*Living aside the more clasical cliches such as the "sensitive child" who sees her but nobody will believe until is too late and the obvious "My son is making mysterius drawings" both very clear at 00:30 ) .Then by giving the deseaced a reason to haunt and take revange beacuse something "really bad" happened to her (I am just assuming this will be the plot) they already humanize something that the spectator could have turned into anything in his imaganation, from that pile of clothes on the chair in their rooms to the shadows coming from outside their windows, its  just scarier when there is no reason for bad things to happen.  Movie Studios need to realize that the beauty of horror movies is simplicity, if you complicated to much you lose your core audience. (Sorry if my english is bad)

text: 0:23 GOOD LORD THIS IS SPOOKY. 0:35 Oh wait, it's just the 'horror' movie that comes out 14 times a year with different names. Nevermind.     Holy crap, who makes those trailers... "Yeah, umm, I think..I think we should, like, show the entire backstory and everything scary about the film in two a half minutes...that would be cool, wouldn't it? What do you guys think?" "Yeah man, awesome, let's totally do that!" I'm very thankful, though. This way I know beforehand that the writers and the director fucked this ONE horror film with at least a little potential in it up, just the way it's apparently necessary.  "Hey, we have that FREAKISHLY scary concept for a horror story, let's just add an in-depth explanation about what exactly is going on to wash anything uncanny about it off and then make it a weak, jumpscare based, pseudo monster movie like the other 400 movies made exactly that way ever since The Ring!"   Sounds legit.

text: Honestly... this kinda look like it sucks compared to the short film. Making it so the woman/creature moves and lunges and attacks removes a lot of the actual creeping fear (the best kind) - which I think is what made the original short so good - and puts it back into the jumpscare category - which is second only to gorefest for lazy terror tropes, imo.  I have nothing but respect for this guy for having been able to make it so far in the business, but I really don't think the idea was all the conducive to a full-fledged movie. I'll probably still go see it since I've got nothing better to see over the summer, but I don't anticipate it to be a utterly TERRIFYING as I found the short to be - both when I watched it originally AND when I rediscovered it a month or so back.

text: tl;dr WHAT HAPPENS IF I SHINE A 500mW LAZER ON IT?  Lets say that this creature can only exist in the shadows or dim light, although no light is preferred. The scene where the woman is flicking the lights on and off tells us that the creature cannot exist in light. It stand to reason that if the creature was doing disappearing act voluntarily, to avoid being in light, then it would have crazy reflexes and no need to chase the characters. It would be over in an instant. So maybe when lit the creature is not visible and is intangible. It can still move, just cannot interact. There are other explanations as well, but I favor this one. So what happens if you put a strong flash light on half of it's body? One of a few things: the parts illuminated disappear, the whole creature disappears, or it hurts the creature.

text: James Wan directed the first Saw movie. The movies became more gory as they went on because the studio thought that was what sold tickets, when in reality, there was very little gore shown in the first movie. It was more about what your brain would conjure up when given the situations the people were in, like the barbed wire trap and the oil and candle trap. They showed very little gore.  Also, James Wan didn't direct this, he produced it while he was directing The Conjuring 2. The guy who did the short, David Sandberg, directed this, which is why I have high hopes for it being good. You have one of the modern horror masters producing, along with a new face with fresh ideas and concepts.

text: the originality  of lights out is questionable. I happen 2 know an old underrated film with lots of similarites with lights out. darkness falls (Jonathan liebesman. 01/24/03)    Both deal with a young child fearing a vengeful female spirit that is affected by the light and an older protagonist that has already dealt with the ghost in the past and come back to aid said child.  Both the older protagonists have also lost a parent to the creature as a child themselves. in fact i couldn't help noticing how the main characters in lights out try to get away from Diana by avoiding being in the lighty areas exactly like what the main characters in darkness falls did to the tooth fairy matilda. did the writers copy these ideas ? lord knows ! but nonetheless i saw lights out it was a very good horror that will never b forgotten.

text: As a comics nerd, I enjoyed going through Diana's special abilities or powers as some people would call them as I watched this film in theaters. In the movie, we witnessed an extraordinary show of power. Diana is able to travel almost any distance with some sort of instantaneous teleportation ability. She also has a keen talent of stealth as well as invulnerability to most physical basic weapons, knives, guns, swords etc. Most of these would not be able to hurt her as her attacker wouldn't be ever able to get close. He/she would have to stay in the light to keep her at a distance which makes it easy to keep her opponent in the defensive. They can either stay in the light where she can't appear or try and battle her in the dark which gives her field advantage. She has also shown to have superhuman strength, superhuman speed and mind manipulation.

text: I love that the director is the one who made the short...and I hope that he understands how hated the LOUD jumpscare is, especially when we learn that better scares can be had without it. I hope he looks to other very effective horror films that don‚Äôt rely on those cheap tricks. The LOUD jump scare has almost become hated in our culture, because it‚Äôs lowbrow, cheap, short-cutting, and lazy. I wonder if filmmakers know that they will be panned by the public and critics for using them way to often and in the wrong way...and I wonder if they even care.
